===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|skinn|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|non}} {{term|skinn|lang=non}} 'animal hide', from {{proto|Germanic|skinþan}} (cf. Old English {{term|scinn|lang=ang}} 'hide', Dutch (Flemish) {{term|schinde|lang=vls}} 'bark', German dialect {{term|Schinde|lang=de}} 'fruit peel'), from pre-Celtic/Germanic *''skento'' (cf. Breton {{term|skant|lang=br}} 'scales', Old Irish {{term|ceinn|lang=sga}} 'id.'), from {{proto|Indo-European|skend-}} 'to split off' (cf. Irish {{term|scainim|lang=ga}} 'I tear, burst', Latin {{term|scindere|lang=la}} 'to split, divide', Sanskrit {{term||chinátti}} 'he splits'), nasal variant of *''skeh₁i-d'' 'to cut'. More at {{l|en|shed}}.

